🏗️ 1. The High Level: The Orchestration Layer

At this level, we deal with the Control Plane. This is purely metadata and "promises" of storage.(Always consumed by worker, As master uses local nodes Volumes Only)

    PVC (PersistentVolumeClaim): The user's request ("I need 10GB of SSD").

    StorageClass: The "Menu" (Defines the provisioner CSI Specs, e.g., HPE 3PAR, AWS EBS).

    PV (PersistentVolume): The actual object representing the backend disk.
#########################################################################################################
A. PersistentVolumeClaim (PVC)

This is the Ticket. It is a request by a user for storage. It defines:

    Size: (e.g., 50Gi)

    Access Mode: * ReadWriteOnce (RWO): Mounted by a single node.

        ReadOnlyMany (ROX): Many nodes can read.

        ReadWriteMany (RWX): Many nodes can read/write (requires NFS/Gluster/Ceph).

B. PersistentVolume (PV)

This is the Resource. It is a specific piece of storage in the cluster. It can be a LUN on your HPE 3PAR, an AWS EBS volume, or a local disk.

C. StorageClass (SC)

This is the Menu. It defines "Profiles" of storage. Instead of manually creating PVs, the admin creates a StorageClass with a Provisioner (CSI driver). When a user creates a PVC, the StorageClass automatically creates the PV.
